5. Application Specifications (How the system is built technically)
a. Architecture
The system follows a three-tier architecture:

Frontend (User Interface)
Provides access for students and teachers
Displays dashboards, grades, attendance, schedules, and document requests
Sends requests to the backend
Backend (Business Logic)
Handles processing of all requests (attendance, grades, document requests)
Manages user authentication and role-based access
Communicates with the database to retrieve and store data
Database
Stores all information about users, classes, attendance, grades, schedules, and documents
Ensures data integrity and security

Interaction Flow:

The user interacts with the frontend → the frontend sends requests to the backend → the backend processes the request → the database stores or retrieves the data → the backend sends results back to the frontend → user sees updated information.
b. Database Model

The system uses a relational database with the following main tables:

Users – stores student and teacher information
Fields: UserID (PK), Name, Role, Email, Password
Classes – stores class information
Fields: ClassID (PK), ClassName, TeacherID (FK)
Attendance – tracks student attendance
Fields: AttendanceID (PK), StudentID (FK), ClassID (FK), Date, Status
Grades – stores student grades
Fields: GradeID (PK), StudentID (FK), ClassID (FK), Grade
Schedules – stores class schedules
Fields: ScheduleID (PK), ClassID (FK), Day, StartTime, EndTime
Documents – manages document requests (Transcript, Attendance Certificate, Enrollment Certificate)
Fields: DocumentID (PK), StudentID (FK), DocumentType, Status, DateRequested

Relationships:

Each student can belong to multiple classes (many-to-many via Classes table)
Each teacher can teach multiple classes (one-to-many)
Attendance and Grades reference valid Students and Classes
Document requests reference valid Students

